    </m:semantics>
   </m:math> has a charge of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>–1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>60</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mtext>19</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:semantics></m:math>, we can convert the current in coulombs per second to electrons per second.</para><para id="import-auto-id2688410">
      <emphasis>Solution</emphasis>
    </para>
    <para id="import-auto-id2016267">Starting with the definition of current, we have</para>
    
    <equation id="eip-414"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mtext>electrons</m:mtext></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mtext>Δ</m:mtext><m:msub><m:mi fontstyle="italic">Q</m:mi><m:mtext>electrons</m:mtext></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>Δ</m:mtext><m:mi fontstyle="italic">t</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mn>–0</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>300 </m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext> 10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/></m:mrow><m:mtext> C</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mtext>s</m:mtext></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{I =  {  {ΔQ}  over  {Δt} }  =  {  {0 "." "300 " times " 10" rSup { size 8{ - 3} } " C"}  over  {"s"} } "."} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation><para id="import-auto-id3064541">We divide this by the charge per electron, so that</para><equation id="eip-199"><m:math>
        <m:semantics>
